            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>To Gaius Domitius Fabius Hermogenes, son of Lucius, of the tribe Palatina, Roman knight, scribe of the curule aediles, adlected decurion, flamen of the divine Hadrian
                   in which priesthood he alone and first sponsored scenic games at his own expense, and aedile. The most splendid order of decurions honoured him with a public funeral
                   and decreed for him an equestrian statue in the forum by subscription at public expense, on account of his devotion and diligence, and in his place it was decided not 
                   to substitute anyone as aedile in consolation to his father Fabius, who on account of the honours having been given to his son, gave 50,000 sesterces to the republic,
                   from the interest of which, every year, on the 13th day before the Kalends of August, his [son's] birthday, 500 denarii are to be distributed among the decurions present in 
                   the forum before his aforementioned statue, and to the decurial cerarius scribes 37 1/2 denarii, to the copyists 12 1/2 denarii, and likewise [25? denarii] to the lictors.  
                   Lucius Fabius Eutychus, son of Spurius, a curiate lictor, cerarius scribe, and copyist, quinquennalis of the guild of Ostian carpenters, and Artoria, his wife [set this up],
                   his parents.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>This is the same C. Domitius Fabius Hermogenes as in <ref target="EmpWor000105.xml">EmpWor000105</ref>, and some of the more ambitious restorations from this monument
                are the result of comparison with the inscription for his statue base in the forum (mentioned here in this inscription). While Hermogenes was elevated to equestrian status, 
                his father – L. Fabius Eutychus – was potentially a freedman (see e.g. Hartmann 2020, 138), and his mother, Artoria, potentially came from a family of craftspeople 
                (see other Artorii: CIL 14.617a, 618, 251). Both father and son take pride in their apparitorial careers, especially in Rome, and which enriched the father to the extent 
                that he could afford to pay 50,000 sesterces to the public treasury for benefactions to be paid out the interest for the sum. In terms of the development of emperor worship 
                at Ostia, it is remarkable that Hermogenes was the first sponsor scenic games for Ostia during his priesthood of the divine Hadrian. Hermogenes' name likely points to his
                adoption or some other close connection with C. Domitius Dexter, who was consul suffectus and later consul ordinarius in 196 CE (Hartmann 2020, 139; D'Arms 1976, 400-401), 
                and who was potentially responsible for his elevation to equestrian status. Hermogenes' public career at Ostia as decurion, flamen of the divine Hadrian, and aedile, 
                seems to have been cut short by his premature death.
                </p> 
            </div>
